            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kevin Morales\u2019s life is a study in steady, deliberate construction, much like the hardware he designs. Raised in the Sacramento suburbs, he was the son of a high school teacher and an auto mechanic. His father\u2019s garage was his first classroom, a place of grease-stained schematics and the satisfying click of a socket wrench. His paternal grandfather, an immigrant from Spain, was a master carpenter, and from him, Kevin inherited a quiet reverence for craftsmanship and the belief that a thing worth doing is worth doing well.\n\nThis practical foundation led him to Cal Poly, San Luis Obispo, where the university\u2019s \u201clearn by doing\u201d ethos perfectly suited his temperament. Armed with a Mechanical Engineering degree, he bypassed the ephemeral world of software startups for the tangibility of hardware. He spent his twenties and early thirties methodically climbing the ranks at a major Silicon Valley electronics firm, proving himself a reliable and innovative leader.\n\nThe key turning point in his life wasn't a promotion, but a move. He and his long-term partner relocated from San Jose to San Francisco\u2019s Inner Sunset, seeking a more vibrant, walkable life. The relationship eventually fractured under the weight of divergent goals, but Kevin stayed. He had fallen for the city\u2019s rhythm\u2014the fog rolling over Twin Peaks, the hum of the N-Judah MUNI line he now rides 3.8 miles to his SoMa office, and the proximity to Golden Gate Park, his weekend sanctuary.\n\nNow a Director of Hardware Engineering, Kevin\u2019s days are a blur of high-stakes meetings and complex problem-solving. His evenings, however, are his own. He finds solace in long runs through the park, cooking simple meals in his quiet apartment, and monthly dinners with a tight-knit circle of friends. At 39, he feels the pull of a future beyond his career. He dreams not of a C-suite title, but of having a small workshop of his own to build custom furniture, mentoring young engineers, and finding a partnership built on shared values rather than shared ambitions. He\u2019s a man who has successfully built a career; now, he\u2019s figuring out how to construct a life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of sawdust in his abuelo's garage, a scent sharper than his father's oil and grease. He was eight. His grandfather guided his small hands, showing him how to cut a perfect dovetail joint. The two pieces of oak slid together with a quiet, solid friction. \"Ves,\" his grandfather had whispered, \"Fuerte. Honesto.\" In that moment, Kevin didn't just learn about wood; he learned about integrity\u2014the deep, quiet satisfaction of making something true and strong. It became his internal compass.\n\n2.\nIt was two in the morning in a San Jose lab, years ago. He was a junior engineer then. After weeks of frustrating work, he flipped the switch on a complex new prototype. There was no dramatic fanfare, just a single green LED illuminating and the faintest, perfectly pitched hum from the internal fan. It was the sound of a thousand tiny, correct decisions. In that silent, humming moment, he felt a satisfaction so profound it eclipsed any ambition for a corner office. This was his work.\n\n3.\nThey stood on the steps at Grandview Park, the city lights sprawling below. She spoke of funding rounds and scaling, her future a glittering ascent. He found himself watching the headlights moving in steady, predictable lines on the streets below. He realized then they weren't looking at the same view. Her gaze was on the sky; his was on the structure. The silence between them wasn't angry, just heavy with the sudden, sad clarity that they were building entirely different things.\n\n4.\nSix months after she left, he was running through Golden Gate Park as the fog began to burn off. He was breathing hard, lost in thought near the Conservatory of Flowers. Then he heard it\u2014the familiar, metallic groan and hum of the N-Judah on Irving Street. It wasn't just noise anymore. It was the city's steady heartbeat, a rhythm promising that life kept moving. He wasn't lonely; he was simply here. For the first time, San Francisco felt less like a place they had moved to, and more like home.\n\n5.\nHe left a brutal all-day meeting about supply chains\u2014a world of spreadsheets and projections. On his walk to the MUNI station, he paused by a simple public park bench. He ran his hand over the worn, smooth slats of redwood, noting the clean bolts and sturdy frame. A deeper satisfaction resonated in that bench than in any project timeline he\u2019d approved that day. It was a physical ache in his chest, a sudden, clear vision of a small workshop and his own two hands making something honest again."
